title: For Sale:  S&W D.A. 45 Hand Ejector 1917 Military WW1 GHS. US Property. Great Shape
postcontent:
Smith & Wesson US ARMY 1917 DA 45
Serial # 116XX

The last one like this to sell on Gunbroker was a higher serial number, and in worst condition and it sold for $865 plus shipping, etc. 

Smith & Wesson produced approximately 163,600 U.S. Army Model 1917 Revolvers between 1917 and 1919. All revolvers were polish blue with 5.5 inch barrels and chambered to shoot the .45 ACP round. This early production revolvers had the ordnance acceptance mark of GHS (Gilbert H. Stewart) which was replaced with the ordnance bomb around April of 1918. The Early Original finish on the S&W M1917 was bright polish blue with case hardened hammer and trigger, they were configured to use the .45 ACP ammo with a moon clip (holds 3 bullets, also allows for extraction). The inspectors mark of Col. Gilbert H. Stewart (GHS) can be found on the left side of the receiver until April, 1918 and then a Ordnance insignia (bomb) until end of production. The serial number can be found on the butt, back of cylinder, underside of barrel, inside right grip, underside of extractor, inside of crane. "United States Property" mark is located on the bottom of the barrel. This is an early issue revolver in a serial range of 1 - c. 12000 seen with “GHS” marking indicating Col. Gilbert H. Stewart as inspector The ordnance acceptance mark of GHS (Col. Gilbert H. Stewart) is only seen on approximately the first 40,000 revolvers. Butt is marked “US Army Model 1917- No 116xx” All matching serial number can be found on the butt, back of cylinder, underside of barrel, underside of extractor, inside of crane and Col. Gilbert H. Stewart S inspector marks on the bottom of the barrel and rear of the cylinder and above the frame assembly number. This early production has the better commercial style bright polish blue with case hardened hammer and trigger finish. Inspector mark of Col. Gilbert H. Stewart (GHS) on the left side of the receiver. This 1917 Military is a rarer Pre flaming bomb marks, pre dull field grade finish, pre June 1918 revolver when Smith & Wesson was nationalized by president Wilson, during WW 1 The government had NATIONALIZED the factory- SEIZED control of it, and declared it a branch of Springfield Armory from that point on the S&W factory was run by division of Springfield Armory and these were United Stated Government manufactured. Less then 25% of the S&W M1917 revolvers are known to have the GHS inspector markings. Has non original serial numbered 1917 Commercial Model style checkered raised diamond walnut grips with the S&W monogram and a notch has been filed in front sight. Approximately 163,600 were made for the U.S. Army between Sept. 17, 1917 to Jan. 1919. The frame is stamped “U.S. ARMY MODEL 1917” in four lines on the butt. “UNITED STATES PROPERTY” is stamped on the bottom of the barrel on the flat. “S&W D.A. 45” is stamped on the barrel’s right side. The top of the barrel is marked “Smith & Wesson Springfield Mass U.S.A. Patented Dec. 17, 1901. Feb. 6, 1906. Sep. 14, 1909.” Lock up is very tight, excellent bore and timing is true and correct. I have shot this gun through all six rounds and it works flawlessly. Very Very nice smooth crisp action. Private seller.

title: For Sale:  UK VZ59 Sight ( UK59 Scope )
postcontent:
UK59 Sight / Scope - private collection - available for purchase.
The Universal Machine Gun - UK Vzor 59 telescopic sight. 
http://vz59.blogspot.com/2014/04/wts-uk59-sights-private-collection.html

To the best of my knowledge the information below is accurate, but I am not an expert, so it might all be entirely incorrect.

UK VZ.59 Sight
Factory: “yal” Meopta Prerau - Prerov factory
Manufactured: 1960's
Tube: 35mm
Magnification: 4x8, non adjustable focus and magnification.
Reticle: Cross with single chevron in center – reticle moves off center with windage and elevation adjustment similar to a Mosin PU sight
Adjustments: Windage and Elevation knobs (black with white numbers) – moves reticle off center in sight tube. Rare sight versions may have silver knobs.
Accessories: Shock absorbing screw-on rubber eye-protection piece; Screw-on yellow Lens Filter (male threads on one side, female threads on other); Screw-on Lens Flash Hider (screws directly on to lens tube, or on to lens filter).
Case: Canvas carry case with belt loop, straps and leather trims; may include a Lens Cleaning Kit (horse hair brush and piece of linen)
Variations of sight: Tube (Day/Night sight) with side port and connection for reticle illumination device; Daytime only optic (rare) without side port connection for reticle illumination.
Illumination/Flashlight device (NOT INCLUDED with sight unless noted - I believe these are pretty rare these days): Flashlight has RGB plastic color filters manually slid into place over the bulb. Sight reticle illumination requires this battery operated illuminator with cable attachment (pretty rare these days) – see the connector on the mount side of the sight tube for bulb port. You can shine a small flashlight or bore light into the port on the side of the sight tube to see how the reticle lights up white in dark environments.
Mount: Clamp mount – securely pinned to sight tube, fits all UK VZ.59 milspec receivers 




THESE OPTICS WERE DESIGNED TO TAKE THE VIBRATION AND SHOCK OF A FULLY AUTOMATIC VZ 59 LIGHT MACHINE GUN OPERATING IN COMBAT ENVIRONMENTS, SO WHILE THEY ARE SIMPLE IN DESIGN AND FUNCTION, THEY ARE VERY ROBUST FOR A CIRCA 1960's SIGHT.


UK59 w/ mount and sight. Copyright 2014


This private collection of optics have been individually inspected and it is believed that each sight functions properly as designed, however I am not an expert. The single cross/chevron reticle correctly moves off center (similar to a Mosin PU scope) in both windage and elevation using the two adjustment knobs on the tube as designed – there is no binding. The glass lenses are clear and not cracked or damaged, but may include tiny cleaning scratches, or inclusions/flaws in the glass as originally issued from the factory. If there are any marks found on the glass it should be noted in the specific description or shown in the pictures. The included sight mount that is securely attached (pinned) to the optic tube is complete and functional and will attach the optic to the UK VZ59 receiver securely as designed. The optional rubber eye piece extension, the yellow daytime lens filter, and the lens flash hider are all intact and included with the optic. There may also be a lens cloth and small brush (“cleaning kit”) and canvas bag (carry case) included so check pictures and the specific description. 

If you find that the optic does not mount securely to a milspec UK59 receiver, or function properly as originally designed and intended, you can return it to me WITHIN 15 DAYS of receipt in the same condition you received it in, for a full refund of your purchase price (not including shipping costs). This does NOT cover any cosmetic issues so review the description and photos carefully.

These optics are acceptable used Czech Military surplus equipment and they will show varying signs of field use potentially including: scratches, missing paint - usually on mounts, field paint touch ups, slight surface rust and/or slight pitting on bare metal surfaces, small dents, and other cosmetic blemishes. I believe these optics are in very acceptable military surplus condition and would rate them as very good to excellent used surplus condition. None of these cosmetic issues will effect the proper mounting and/or operation of the optic. I have tried my best to note any cosmetic issues in the specific description and show them in the pictures. Please contact me with any questions or for more pictures before purchase as I will not entertain any returns for cosmetic issues. 

Specific descriptions for current stock:

See photos in posts for details on included parts and condition. 

Comments and questions are welcome.
If you are a Semi-Auto Marcolmar owner (or you want to be) contact me directly for special pricing. 

Descriptions, photos and URL link:

Only 2 left !  All the rest have sold.

http://vz59.blogspot.com/2014/04/wts-uk59-sights-private-collection.html

This is a Pre-ban Colt AR15 with an SP1 Receiver. This is the 1st civilian version of the military M16 to be issued to the public. It is in really good condition and will make someone a great trophy gun. It is in great firing condition and has not been fired since 1995. It has spent it's life in a gun safe ever since. Everyone that see's it in our store thinks that it is a fully automatic M16 and no one wants the newer AR15 after seeing it's past in this one. It is known for it's triangular hand guard and bayonet lug and some other features listed below. The features below were shared with the M16. 

Slickside The earliest version of the AR-15 upper receiver which can easily be identified by its lack of forward assist and brass deflector. This type of receiver was used on the original M16, USAF weapons, and the SP1 civilian rifle. 

The bayonet lug on AR-15 rifles is a small protrusion on the front underside of the gas block. This is present on the majority of Colt AR-15 military rifles, but is omitted in the case of some carbines as it is redundant due to the bayonet requiring a longer barrel to be mounted onto. It is also absent from a number of civilian rifles, most notably the Match Target rifles, in order to comply with various laws and regulations. 

The iconic M16 flash hider often referred to as the “Birdcage”, and was on a closed design to address problems encountered with the duckbill type flash hiders snagging on vegetation. Introduced on the M16A1, it has 6 ports equally distributed around the flash hider.
